===Etymology===
From sense {{m|en|poll||head}} for “uniform tax per individual”; from sense {{m|en|poll||voting place}} for “tax required to vote”.

===Noun===
{{en-noun|es}}

# A [[tax]] determined as a uniform, fixed amount per [[individual]].
# {{lb|en|US}} A tax that must be paid in order to vote.

====Usage notes====
* In the US, generally used today to refer to taxes that must be paid in order to vote, with high risk of confusion if used for “head tax”. Further, the term has strong negative connotations, due to these taxes discriminating against blacks – see {{w|Jim Crow laws}}.
* In the UK, the term was used for the tax levied in England which lead to the [[w:Peasants' Revolt|Peasants' Revolt]] in 1381. It was then applied to the [[w:Community Charge|Community Charge]], a tax for local government services that was abolished in 1993.

